In this work pure and rhodium doped hematite have been studied using DFT through the SIESTA simulations package38. The generalized gradient approximation (GGA) with the exchange correlation authors, Revised Perdew-Burke Ernzehof (RPBE)39 has been used for the optimization of all geometries. A hybrid DFT with 75% local density approximation (LDA) and 25% generalized gradient approximation (GGA) has been widely used in the past to calculate the structural parameters of various materials. However, transition metals have highly correlated electrons and most of the DFT techniques incorrectly compute the electronic properties of the metal oxides. For such materials, the above-mentioned techniques also incorrectly describe the columbic repulsion in the localized d state electrons40. In order to accurately calculate the electronic band structure and density of states (DOS) we have implemented the DFT + U technique in this work. We have used a 1×1×1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
