The refractive index depends on the physical properties of a material and the wavelength of propagating light. An increase in the refractive index of rhodium doped hematite in comparison with pure hematite (shown in Fig. 10a) indicates high density and polarizability of the material due to the rhodium 4d and 5s contributions which attenuate the propagating light58. As shown in Fig. 10b, an increase in the extinction coefficient indicates that the surface of rhodium doped hematite absorbs more light than the pristine hematite which allows for more permeation of light and hence improved optical properties of the material. The measured values of the refractive index and the extinction coefficient are given in Table 4.Figure 10
